---
import DocsLayout from "../layouts/DocsLayout.astro";
---

<DocsLayout title="FAQ — hemingway-ai" heading="FAQ">
  <h2>General</h2>

  <details>
    <summary>What is hemingway?</summary>
    <p>
      Hemingway is an AI-powered copy editing overlay for marketing sites. It
      runs as a local development tool — you select text on your live site, see
      Claude-generated alternatives, and apply them with one click.
    </p>
  </details>

  <details>
    <summary>Who is it for?</summary>
    <p>
      Developers and marketing teams who iterate on website copy. If you're tired
      of rewriting headlines in a spreadsheet, hemingway lets you edit copy
      directly on the live page.
    </p>
  </details>

  <details>
    <summary>Is it free?</summary>
    <p>
      Yes, hemingway is MIT licensed and free to use. You'll need your own
      Anthropic API key, which has its own pricing.
    </p>
  </details>

  <h2>Setup</h2>

  <details>
    <summary>What frameworks does it work with?</summary>
    <p>
      Any framework that renders HTML. React, Vue, Svelte, Astro, Next.js, plain
      HTML — just add a script tag or use the React component.
    </p>
  </details>

  <details>
    <summary>What AI models are supported?</summary>
    <p>
      Claude models via the Anthropic API. The default is claude-sonnet-4-6, but
      you can configure any Claude model in your config file.
    </p>
  </details>

  <details>
    <summary>Do I need an API key?</summary>
    <p>
      Yes, you need an Anthropic API key. Set it as the
      <code>ANTHROPIC_API_KEY</code> environment variable before starting the
      server.
    </p>
  </details>

  <h2>Usage</h2>

  <details>
    <summary>How does write-back work?</summary>
    <p>
      When you apply an alternative, hemingway searches your source files for the
      original text using heuristic matching. It handles HTML entities, curly
      quotes, and whitespace variations, and scores matches by surrounding
      context (tag names, CSS classes) to find the right location.
    </p>
  </details>

  <details>
    <summary>What if it picks the wrong file?</summary>
    <p>
      Configure <code>sourcePatterns</code> in your config to narrow the search
      scope. For example, <code>["src/components/**/*.tsx"]</code> limits
      write-back to your component files.
    </p>
  </details>

  <details>
    <summary>Can I use it in production?</summary>
    <p>
      No, hemingway is a development tool. The server logs a warning if
      <code>NODE_ENV</code> is set to <code>production</code>. It's designed for
      iterating on copy during development, not for runtime use.
    </p>
  </details>

  <details>
    <summary>Does it support inline editing?</summary>
    <p>
      Yes, double-click any text element to edit it directly in the browser.
      Press Enter or click away to commit the change back to your source file.
    </p>
  </details>

  <h2>Privacy &amp; Security</h2>

  <details>
    <summary>Does my copy leave my machine?</summary>
    <p>
      Only to Anthropic's API for generating alternatives. Hemingway makes no
      other external network calls. Your copy is never stored on any third-party
      server.
    </p>
  </details>

  <details>
    <summary>Is it safe to use with client code?</summary>
    <p>
      Yes, hemingway runs entirely on localhost. The server binds to
      <code>127.0.0.1</code> by default and the overlay communicates only with
      the local server.
    </p>
  </details>
</DocsLayout>
